  "context_summary": "52-year-old man presents with hearing loss in his right ear that he noticed upon waking two days ago. He describes it as 'like the ear is plugged' with associated tinnitus. He denies pain, discharge, or trauma. No prior ear problems. He initially assumed it was wax and tried over-the-counter drops without relief. The doctor has confirmed no visible cerumen impaction or effusion on otoscopy and is about to decide whether this requires urgent audiometry and steroid treatment versus routine referral.",
  "good_next_question": "Can you tell me exactly when you first noticed the hearing loss, and did it come on all at once or did it get worse gradually over a few days?",
  "rationale": "Establishing a precise onset window is the single most time-sensitive discriminator in this presentation. Sudden sensorineural hearing loss (SSNHL) is an otologic emergency: outcomes are strongly tied to starting corticosteroids within 2 weeks of onset, with the best results inside 72 hours. This patient already assumed it was wax and self-treated with drops before seeking care — a common pattern in SSNHL, where patients lose days of the treatable window to home remedies before recognizing this isn't ordinary blockage. That delay is exactly why pinning down the exact onset date matters here: it tells the doctor whether the intervention window is still open (favoring emergent audiometry and immediate steroids) or has already closed (shifting the goal toward documentation and counseling on prognosis rather than urgent treatment). A gradual onset over weeks, by contrast, would point away from SSNHL toward a retrocochlear process (e.g., vestibular schwannoma), changing the workup to MRI instead. Asking about pain or discharge first is weaker because otoscopy has already excluded the common conductive causes; onset timing is what determines both the diagnosis and whether urgent treatment is still actionable.",
  "tags": [
    "ent",
    "sudden_sensorineural_hearing_loss",
    "ssnhl",
    "otologic_emergency",
    "hearing_loss",
    "adult",
    "male"
  ],
